\begin{frame}
\frametitle{About the Challenge}
Quantum City hosts an online challenge to demonstrate and assess the use of quantum technology in Alberta's energy industry. The challenge, in collaboration with Amazon Web Services, aims to explore quantum solutions for modern energy problems, sponsored by two Alberta-based energy organizations.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Challenge Approach}
The challenge acknowledges the nascent state of quantum computing, seeking innovative ideas for future applications. Submissions may include proof of concept solutions, hybrid quantum-classical approaches, and more, utilizing current quantum simulators and devices.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Problem Statement}
The focus is on smart scheduling for EV charging in a hypothetical city. The city faces challenges in managing electricity supply constraints and balancing charging hub supply with EV charging demands. The task is to develop quantum solutions for this combinatorial optimization problem.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Solution Requirements}
Solutions should compare against classical models, considering computational time, optimization accuracy, total energy demands, and hardware usage. Detailed quantum noise and error metrics are expected to provide insights into the quantum capabilities for optimization problems.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Data Sources}
Participants are provided with a mathematical problem formulation, mock datasets, and precise optimization objectives. The mock scenario and data are based on Statistics Canada data and other public sources, tailored for the challenge.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Technical Glossary}
The challenge includes a glossary of terms related to the electricity industry, vital for understanding the detailed problem statement. This includes definitions of electric current, charge, charging variables, EVs, and more.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Detailed Problem Statement}
The city's problem involves a total of 25,000 EVs and a public charging hub with specific charging capacities. The challenge includes assumptions about EV usage, energy requirements, and charging infrastructure, with a focus on Level 2 chargers.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Objective Functions}
The challenge outlines key objective functions to optimize, such as quick charging, non-completion penalty, and minimizing total load variations. Participants are encouraged to experiment with these functions to enhance optimization under realistic constraints.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Conclusion}
The Quantum City Challenge presents a unique opportunity to explore the potential of quantum computing in addressing real-world energy problems. Participants are encouraged to bring innovative ideas and solutions to the forefront of quantum technology application.
\end{frame}

